Create Client Keystore (JKS)
Original (runmqckm)
runmqckm -keydb -create -db filename.jks -pw <pwd> -type jks
✅ keytool Equivalent
keytool -genkeypair \
  -alias ibmmq-client \
  -keyalg RSA \
  -keysize 2048 \
  -validity 730 \
  -keystore filename.jks \
  -storetype JKS \
  -storepass <pwd> \
  -keypass <pwd> \
  -dname "CN=APPA_DEV,O=AP,OU=AUTHENC,L=MQCDEV,C=HK"

Replace DN based on your env:

Non-Prod Example:
CN=<AppCode>_DEV
L=MQCDEV
OU=AUTHENC
O=AP/EU/NA
C=HK/GB/US/FR
Prod Example:
CN=<AppCode>_PROD
L=MQCPROD
OU=AUTHENC
O=AP/EU/NA
C=HK/GB/US/FR
🔁 2. Create CSR (Certificate Request)
Original
runmqckm -certreq -create ...
✅ keytool Equivalent
keytool -certreq \
  -alias ibmmq-client \
  -file client.req \
  -keystore filename.jks \
  -storepass <pwd>

That client.req is what you send to SNOW.

🔁 3. Import Root & Intermediate Certificates

Original commands were importing:

HSBC Issuing CA02-G2

HSBC ORCA G2

⚠️ IMPORTANT: With keytool you MUST import CA first, before importing signed cert.

Import Root CA
keytool -importcert \
  -alias root-ca \
  -file HSBC_ORCA_G2.cer \
  -keystore filename.jks \
  -storepass <pwd> \
  -noprompt
Import Intermediate CA
keytool -importcert \
  -alias issuing-ca \
  -file HSBC_Issuing_CA02_G2.cer \
  -keystore filename.jks \
  -storepass <pwd> \
  -noprompt
🔁 4. Import Signed Certificate (after SNOW returns it)

Original:

runmqckm -cert -receive ...
✅ keytool Equivalent

If certificate is Base64 (.cer ASCII):

keytool -importcert \
  -alias ibmmq-client \
  -file signed_cert.cer \
  -keystore filename.jks \
  -storepass <pwd>

⚠️ Alias must match the original keypair alias (ibmmq-client).

This attaches the signed cert to your private key.

🔁 5. Verify Keystore
List content
keytool -list -v \
  -keystore filename.jks \
  -storepass <pwd>

You should see:

PrivateKeyEntry → ibmmq-client

Certificate chain length: 3

Client

Intermediate

Root

If chain length is 1 → you did something wrong.

🔁 6. (Optional) Create Separate Truststore for MQ

Kafka Connect usually uses:

keystore → client cert

truststore → server CA

Create truststore:

keytool -importcert \
  -alias mq-root \
  -file HSBC_ORCA_G2.cer \
  -keystore mq-truststore.jks \
  -storetype JKS \
  -storepass <pwd> \
  -noprompt

If MQ server cert signed by intermediate → also import intermediate.

🔥 What Kafka MQ Sink Connector Needs

In connector config:

ssl.keystore.location=/path/filename.jks
ssl.keystore.password=<pwd>
ssl.key.password=<pwd>

ssl.truststore.location=/path/mq-truststore.jks
ssl.truststore.password=<pwd>
⚠️ Critical Differences vs runmqckm
runmqckm	keytool
Trust enable flag	Not needed
DB vs JKS distinction	Must specify -storetype JKS
Label	Alias
Auto chain handling	Must import CA first
💣 Common Mistakes I See in MQ + Kafka

Importing signed cert before CA

Using different alias when importing signed cert

Forgetting intermediate CA

Using PKCS12 instead of JKS

Chain length = 1 → handshake fails

DN mismatch vs what MQ expects

